node.text:
Did you know that orangutans build a new nest up in a tree every night to sleep in?  Here you see a female Bornean Orangutan in Gunung Palung, putting the final touches on her nest before she and her baby settle down for the night.  She made a platform by bending branches over, and is now just adding a “mattress” or “pillow” of leaves before she lies down. @RussLaman and I shot this video after a long day of following this orangutan through the forest with the research team from @SaveWildOrangutans.  It’s nice when orangutans make a nest before dark, you can get a shot, and then head back to base camp yourself for a bit of rest after carrying camera gear through the forest all day.
-
To learn more about the lives of wild orangutans, and our orangutan research and conservation at #GunungPalungNationalPark in Indonesian Borneo, follow @SaveWildOrangutans.  @tanagupa #orangutan #Indonesia #Borneo #shotonred @reddigitalcinema

node.text:
Not all Birds-of-Paradise have bright colored plumes.  Some have amazing super-black plumage to better show off ornaments like the bright neck feathers of this Magnificent Riflebird filmed by @TimLaman and Ed Scholes in West Papua, Indonesia for the @BirdsofParadiseProject. Listen to the audio to hear the amazing sounds the male’s wings make, which is all part of his display to try to impress a female.
Ed and I spent over 80 hours in blinds to film this sequence.  The male came every day and called from this vine, but we only had a couple brief visits by a female in all that time.  Photographing Birds-of-Paradise requires a lot of patience, but its worth it because sharing these stories is so important for bringing attention to the value of Papua’s forests.  Right now, the guardians of these forests, the landowners who live there, have lost an important income source from international visitors coming to see their birds.  I’m sure you’d like to help, so I’m doing a print sale as a fundraiser to help them out.  Please check out my Birds-of-Paradise collection of prints at my online store in bio, or at www.timlamanfineart.com.  50% of all BoP print proceeds will go to people in Papua. 
Follow @TimLaman and @BirdsofParadiseProject for all things bird-of-paradise!

node.text:
Video by @TimLaman and Ed Scholes.  Sometimes, filming expeditions can yield surprising scientific discoveries, especially in remote places like the island of New Guinea.  On our filming trips to the Arfak Mountains in West Papua a while back for the Netflix documentaries “Our Planet” and “Dancing with the Birds” we located a display site and filmed the local variety of the Superb Bird-of-Paradise displaying for the first time.  This led to our documentation, especially after subsequent trips for the Cornell Lab of Ornithology, that this was a distinct species of Bird-of-Paradise, now called the Vogelkop Superb Bird-of-Paradise.  If you haven’t seen the short video explaining this discovery on the Cornell Youtube channel, I’m sharing it again here.  Watch on IGTV and turn your phone to see it full screen.
 
I find my natural history filmmaking work especially satisfying when we can make a contribution to scientific knowledge and hopefully also conservation awareness while making films that entertain and educate.  That’s when it all comes together.  A discovery like an unknown bird-of-paradise just shows how much more we have to learn about the biodiversity of the New Guinea region.
 
#birdsofparadise #superbbirdofparadise #papua @CornellBirds #CornellLabofOrnithology #DancingwiththeBirds  #OurPlanet

Photos by @TimLaman.  Godwit foraging in the surf zone at sunset, San Diego, 2011.  Found this image today in my archives as I work my way through various personal trips, looking for any undiscovered, artistic bird images that might fit into the new book project I’m working on of my bird photography from around the world.  I like this one quite a lot, especially the full width version.  Its exactly the type of overlooked artistic shot from a never published personal trip that I’m looking for for my book.
But all I have are silhouette shots.  Can any of you bird nerds out their recognize which Godwit species this is just from the shape?  I can’t.  It was taken in San Diego in August.  Thanks for any thoughts, as it would be nice to have the correct species name if I can.  In the third shot, you can see the godwit at left with some willets for size reference.

Bye the way I’m giving away a Bird-of-Paradise print at the end of August.  Sign up for my newsletter at link in my profile to get entered.  Good luck!

Photo by @TimLaman.  To celebrate #WorldElephantDay today, I wanted to share this image from one of most memorable elephant encounters ever.  We rounded a bend in the river, deep in the Borneo rainforest, and encountered a whole group of elephants crossing the river, playing in the water, snorkeling, and generally looking like they were having a great time.  This youngster was splashing with his trunk as he swam across.  These elephants are a very unique population, the “Borneo Pygmy Elephant”, a subspecies of Asian Elephant (Elephas maximus borneensis), and their uniqueness makes them a high priority for conservation.  Lets hope we have the wisdom to leave space on our planet for elephants and all the other creatures that make it so special.  Spread the word, and take time today to see how you can help with elephant conservation!
#elephant #borneoelephant #borneypygmyelephant #sabah #malaysia #kinabatanganriver #conservation #wildlifephotography #snorkeling #borneobiodiversity

Males like this one display high in the canopy, and required some tricky tree climbing and blind building to get this shot. Video by @TimLaman.  I was excited to learn that the TV series I worked on for Netflix called “Attenborough’s Life in Color” is up for multiple awards at the Jackson Wild Film Festival.  This is a brief sample of the Magnificent Bird-of-Paradise courtship behavior that I filmed for the program, which features an incredible display by the male of his bright green breast shield toward the female above him.  We are pretty sure this is the first time it has ever been filmed from above, from the female’s perspective, which after all is what matters to the birds.
If you haven’t seen it, you can find the program on Netflix!
And if you are a Bird-of-Paradise fan, you might like to know that I now have prints of the Magnificent Bird-of-Paradise (and many other species) in my online gallery at www.timlaman.com (link in bio).

Photo by @TimLaman.  Humpback among the icebergs, Andvord Bay, Antarctica.  It was a perfectly calm monochromatic day along the Antarctic peninsula as our ship cruised slowly among the icebergs in Andvord Bay a few years ago.  I captured this peaceful moment as a feeding humpback whale lifted its flukes to dive.  This is one of my images now available as a Limited Edition print in my Fine Art store.  Please visit www.timlamanfineart.com (link also in bio) for details and to see my entire collection.

Humpback whales have made a remarkable comeback since the pressure from the whaling industry in the 20th century has subsided, and are a symbol of hope for our planet.  I have had amazing encounters with them on their southern feeding grounds in Antarctica (where whales like this one come to feed on krill during the souther summer), on their northern feeding grounds off Massachusetts, and also at their breeding and calving areas in Panama, among other sites.  It is awe inspiring to encounter one of these giant creatures in their element and I always look forward to my next encounter.  Whale watching is incredibly popular, and I know many of you must have had similar experiences near where I live in New England, or in far off Antarctica.  I hope you enjoy this peaceful encounter that I was able to capture.  The Limited Edition is printed at 24x48 inches on recycled archival aluminum and looks stunning.

#whale #humpbackwhale #antarctica #fineart #limitededition #monochrome #black&white #simplicity

Behind the scenes shots from the making of our Loon film.  Sign up for my newsletter at my link in profile to get my next newsletter where I’ll share more about our family project to film loons in Maine.  My son @RussLaman and I filmed, my daughter Jessica helped in the field, recorded sounds, and also narrated the film.  It was a fun family project during covid.  If you haven’t seen it, please check out the 10 min short film “Loons of Mount Desert Island” also at my link in profile.  We spent some quality time with these wonderful birds and hope everyone can develop a greater appreciation for them and the clean waters of northern lakes that they need for breeding.

Many thanks to Somes Meynell Wildlife Sanctuary (somesmeynell.org) and Acadia National Park for their support!

And if you’re interested in my online wildlife photo course, don’t forget to give me some feedback at my link in bio!
